    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "oh okay. so if it's mostly caused by the jet stream or wind shear, does that mean it's always happening in certain altitudes? like is there a specific way the wind shifts that makes it go from smooth air to crazy turbulence all of a sudden?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, CAT is more commonly associated with high-altitude regions, typically above 20,000 feet. The jet stream, which is a fast-moving band of air, often plays a role in creating CAT in these areas. Wind shear can occur suddenly when the jet stream intersects with other weather systems, such as approaches to fronts or mountainous regions, resulting in drastic changes in air speed and pressure. This can cause turbulence to develop rapidly, often without warning.",
      "source": "target",
